{
  "answer": "**The *Manusmṛti* (also known as the *Laws of Manu*), Chapter 1, opens with a cosmogony matching this description.**[^1]\n\nThe divine Self-existent One (Svayambhu) creates a golden egg from his seed in the primordial waters:\n\n> That seed became a golden egg, in splendor like the thousand-rayed sun; in it he himself was born as Brahma, the great father of all the worlds. // Mn_1.9 //[^2]\n\nAfter dwelling in the egg for a year, he splits it:\n\n> After dwelling in that egg for a full year, that divine Lord, by his own contemplation, split the egg in two. // Mn_1.12 //[^3]\n\n> And with those two halves he formed the heavens and the earth, and between them the middle region, the eight directions, and the eternal abode of the waters. // Mn_1.13 //[^4]\n\nHe then produces the four social orders (*varnas*):\n\n> And for the sake of the prosperity of the worlds, he caused the Brahmana, the Kshatriya, the Vaishya, and the Shudra to emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet. // Mn_1.31 //[^5]\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Manusmṛti*, [Mn_1.9](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-153021).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, [Mn_1.12](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-cd6713).\n\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, [Mn_1.13](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-3bd729).\n\n[^5]: *Manusmṛti*, [Mn_1.31](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-13a2db).",
